
### Msg Type Scenario
The Msg Type scenario is utilized for commands that return text-based responses directly from DirMaint, such as queries that retrieve configuration or status information from the user directory. For example, commands like DIRM FOR LNXTOOL2 PRIVCLASS ? or DIRM FOR LNXTOOL2 CRYPTO ? generate output that is purely informational text, which is transmitted as a message payload without any file attachments.

**Request from Linux (Msg Type For commands that do not include file attachments)**

```
msglen
headerlen
<header begin>
    timestamp = <cp timestamp>
    user = <linux guest>
    os_user = <linux os user>
    pid = <linux os pid>
    msg_part = 1/n
    req_type = 0    <file=1 / msg_only=0>
    data_len = <no. of chars of data>
<header end>
<Data of length data_len >
```

| Field | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| msglen | Total length of the complete message |
| headerlen | Length of the header section |
| timestamp | CP timestamp when the message was generated |
| user | Guest user ID (invoker) |
| os_user | Linux OS username |
| pid | Linux process ID |
| msg_part | Current message part number (e.g., 1/n, 2/n) |
| req_type | 0 = text-only |
| data_len | Length of the data payload |
| data | The actual command text |

<br>

**Response from DirMaint (Msg Type)**

```
msglen
headerlen
<header begin>
    timestamp = <cp timestamp>
    user = DirMaint
    msg_part = 1/n
    return_code = 0    <success=0 / error=1>
    resp_type = 0      <file=1 / msg_only=0>
    data_len = <no. of chars of data>
<header end>
<Data of length data_len >
```

| Field | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| msglen | Total length of the complete message |
| headerlen | Length of the header section |
| timestamp | CP timestamp when the response was generated |
| user | DirMaint (service machine identifier) |
| msg_part | Current message part number |
| return_code | 0 = success, 1 = error |
| resp_type | 0 = text-only |
| data_len | Length of the data payload |
| data | The response text |

<br>

### File Type Scenario
The File Type scenario is employed for commands that involve the exchange of SPOOL files between DirMaint and the Linux guest, such as directory reviews or retrievals. For instance, commands like DIRM FOR LNXTOOL2 REV or DIRM FOR LNXTOOL2 GET generate output in the form of SPOOL files (e.g., LNXTOOL2 DIRECT A or LNXTOOL2 DIRECT B), which contain the complete directory entry data. These files are parsed by the DirMaint service machine and transmitted as IUCV messages with file metadata and content, enabling the VMDIR client to reconstruct and save the file locally. 

**Request from Linux**
For commands that include file attachments:

```
msglen
headerlen
<header begin>
    timestamp = <cp timestamp>
    user = <guest>
    os_user = <linux os user>
    pid = <linux os pid>
    msg_part = 1/n
    req_type = 1    <file=1 / msg_only=0>
    data_len = <no. of chars of data>
    file_count = <int>
<header end>
<Data of length data_len >
<file1_name>.<filetype>.<filelen_in_chars>
<file1_data of length filelen_in_chars >

<file2_name>.<filetype>.<filelen_in_chars>
<file2_data of length filelen_in_chars >
```

| Field | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| msglen | Total length of the complete message |
| headerlen | Length of the header section |
| timestamp | CP timestamp when the message was generated |
| user | Guest user ID (invoker) |
| os_user | Linux OS username |
| pid | Linux process ID |
| msg_part | Current message part number (e.g., 1/n) |
| req_type | 1 = includes file data |
| data_len | Length of the data payload (header + file metadata + file data) |
| file_count | Number of files being transmitted |
| file1_name | Name of the first file |
| filetype | Type/extension of the file |
| filelen_in_chars | Length of the file data in characters |
| file1_data | The actual file content |

<br>

**Response from DirMaint + File**
For responses that include file data:

```
msglen
headerlen
<header begin>
    timestamp = <cp timestamp>
    user = DirMaint
    msg_part = 1/n
    return_code = 0    <success=0 / error=1>
    resp_type = 1      <file=1 / msg_only=0>
    data_len = <no. of chars of data>
    file_count = <int>
<header end>
<Data of length data_len >
<file1_name>.<filetype>.<filelen_in_chars>
<file1_data of length filelen_in_chars >

<file2_name>.<filetype>.<filelen_in_chars>
<file2_data of length filelen_in_chars >
```

| Field | Description |
|-------|-------------|
| msglen | Total length of the complete message |
| headerlen | Length of the header section |
| timestamp | CP timestamp when the response was generated |
| user | DirMaint (service machine identifier) |
| msg_part | Current message part number |
| return_code | 0 = success, 1 = error |
| resp_type | 1 = includes file data |
| data_len | Length of the data payload |
| file_count | Number of files being transmitted |

